dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Shahzad c Cameron-Dow b Murtagh 6 (4b 0x4 1x6) SR: 150

dismissalComment.html: leading edge caught at mid-off Shahzad is staying put, he thinks it might have bounced in front of the fielder. And the umpires think so too, with the soft signal being not out. This was angled into Shahzad and he wanted to flick it away, but a hint of movement meant he got the leading edge. Cameron-Dow at mid-off ran in and went low to grab the ball. But does he have fingers underneath the ball? He certainly appears to have done so. And the third umpire agrees! Shahzad has to go. Six off the first ball, out off the fourth.

dismissalText.commentary: Paul Stirling lbw b Rashid Khan 70 (88b 7x4 2x6) SR: 79.54

dismissalComment.html: given lbw and Stirling's not happy The ball was another peach, landed on middle and off and turned away, struck him on the pad. He was going back and trying to defend. commentTextItems.html: full toss down the legside, tickled away down to fine-leg and that's the match

commentPostTextItems.html: That's all from Saurabh, Thilak and me. Thanks for joining and we look forward to your company for the Test match on the 15th.
Andy Balbirnie is the man of the series All the batters are aware how good their spinners are. I just kind of knew my game, we watched a lot of their footage.
Asghar Afghan It was a good series, we are targeting the world cup, so we made changes in every match. Top order's a concern, the Test match should offer an opportunity.

8.00pm After being walloped in the T20Is and trailing twice during the ODIs, Ireland have done superbly to draw level, with a comprehensive five-wicket win here. Andy Balbirnie was a major contributor again, anchoring the chase to perfection with 91-ball 68 to follow up on his match winning hundred earlier. But Paul Stirling was the star, his charge curtailed by a contentious lbw decision that he was visibly furious about. His 88-ball 70 brought Ireland within sniffing distance of the target and the middle-order did enough to take them home without much drama. The pitch certainly got better to bat on under lights, but Ireland still had a strong spin attack to contend with and they did so beautifully. Afghanistan would be disappointed but they've been in an experimental mode through the series, making three or four changes on an average to test their bench, leading into the World Cup.

dismissalComment.html: given lbw and Stirling's not happy The ball was another peach, landed on middle and off and turned away, struck him on the pad. He was going back and trying to defend. But not only would the turn have taken it past the off stump, he was also struck outside the line. Big wicket that, and very unlucky for Ireland and Stirling, who has to go after playing a gem

milestones.description: Mohammad Nabi has become the top scorer for AFG in ODIs with 2565 runs, going past Shahzad's 2556
Shahzad has scored 18 fifty-plus scores in ODIs, the most for AFG breaking Rahmat Shah's record
Paul Stirling has broken the record for most ducks (9) in ODIs for IRE, going past Porterfield's 9
